<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-217-272 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 387 177</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Feb 25 1991 v13 n8 pS9(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Will OOP Basic fulfill Gates' vision of the future? (objectoriented programming) (Windows special section)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnston, Stuart J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft Corp is developing an 'object-oriented' version of theBASIC programming language for its Windows graphical userinterface, but the promised cross-application macro controlcapabilities will not be available until at least 1993.andP;  Interimversions of Windows Basic may nevertheless serve Microsoft'svision of an object-oriented future by providing a programminglanguage for Windows database applications.andP;  Microsoft plans toprovide a complete object-oriented user environment in anext-generation version of Windows based on 'informational datatypes' manipulated via 'command objects.' It will include anobject-oriented file system and truly object oriented shell.andO;These changes are the result of several technologies merging.andO;Compiled versions of BASIC have been available for several years,and the Quick Basic compiler will be bundled with DOS 5.0.andO;Microsoft Word for Windows includes a Basic-like macro language,Word Basic.andP;  Windows Basic will ultimately evolve into atransparent, easy-to-use facility for automating complex tasks byperforming them once; recorded keystrokes and mouse clicks will betransformed into editable Basic code.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (Programming).andO;Topic:     BASICGraphical User InterfaceObject-Oriented ProgrammingStrategic PlanningProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Integration perspective. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>